17:41.828 --> 17:43.963
Love, Melody.

17:48.201 --> 17:50.802
I don't think anyone named
Melody goes to this school.

17:50.803 --> 17:53.605
You know, Melody might not
even be her real name.

17:53.606 --> 17:56.108
Do you recognize
the handwriting at all?

17:56.109 --> 17:58.343
It's nice. It's very elegant.

17:58.344 --> 18:01.080
I should only be so lucky
with my students.

18:02.749 --> 18:04.883
(SIGHS) What do you think?

18:04.884 --> 18:07.519
I mean, what should I do?
Who is she?

18:07.520 --> 18:09.988
Maybe you already met her.
Have you met anyone recently?

18:09.989 --> 18:11.857
Not really, I mean…

18:11.858 --> 18:13.859
I have to find her, though.

18:13.860 --> 18:16.362
(WHISPERS)
Oh, I have a great idea.

18:18.531 --> 18:22.234
So you walk up to every girl
that crosses your path,

18:22.235 --> 18:23.969
both inside and outside
of class…

18:23.970 --> 18:26.638
- Yeah?
- And you shout…

18:26.639 --> 18:28.507
(WHISPERING) "Melody!"

18:28.508 --> 18:30.610
"Melody!"

18:31.244 --> 18:33.379
See what happens.

18:35.715 --> 18:39.584
That… That's it?
That's your advice?

18:39.585 --> 18:40.853
Yup.

18:44.457 --> 18:46.059
Seriously?

18:55.768 --> 18:57.570
(WHISPERS) Melody?

18:58.838 --> 19:00.440
Melody?

19:03.543 --> 19:05.577
(WHISPERING) Hey, Melody?

19:05.578 --> 19:07.046
Melody?

19:08.247 --> 19:10.148
(SHOUTS) Melody.

19:10.149 --> 19:11.217
Melody.

19:11.884 --> 19:14.520
Uh, Melody? Melody? Melody?

19:15.855 --> 19:16.989
Uh, Mel… (GRUNTS)

19:16.990 --> 19:19.459
Melody? Melody?
Melody? Melody?

19:41.314 --> 19:42.582
(PA BUZZING)

19:46.753 --> 19:48.653
(TAP ECHOING)

19:48.654 --> 19:50.222
(CLEARS THROAT)

19:50.223 --> 19:52.591
SIDNEY: (OVER PA)
Uh, excuse me.

19:52.592 --> 19:55.660
Pardon the announcement. Um…

19:55.661 --> 20:00.699
But would anyone named Melody

20:00.700 --> 20:02.934
please report
to the front office.

20:02.935 --> 20:05.237
I repeat, anyone named Melody,

20:05.238 --> 20:08.507
uh, please report to the
front office immediately.

20:08.508 --> 20:09.442
This is an urgent matter.

20:09.443 --> 20:10.776
Um…

20:10.777 --> 20:13.245
Anybody who writes under
the pseudonym, Melody, just…

20:13.246 --> 20:16.315
- Just come to the front…
- (PA BUZZES)

20:28.628 --> 20:29.895
HAROLD:
Get outta here, you savages.

20:29.896 --> 20:31.129
Go eat some hors d'oeuvres.

20:31.130 --> 20:32.597
Feed on the blood of the young,

20:32.598 --> 20:33.932
whatever it is you do.

20:33.933 --> 20:37.202
Here, all the greats
drink whiskey.

20:37.203 --> 20:38.270
That's a fact.

20:38.271 --> 20:40.238
How soon before I can go?

20:40.239 --> 20:43.275
It's like throwing a party
for Silvia Plath.

20:43.276 --> 20:45.744
Come on, I have to talk
to you about something.

20:45.745 --> 20:47.379
The Big P.

20:47.380 --> 20:50.248
I need you to be
encouraged by it.

20:50.249 --> 20:52.117
I want you to embrace it.

20:52.118 --> 20:54.219
It means a lot
to a lot of people.

20:54.220 --> 20:57.422
Not least of which,
should be you.

20:57.423 --> 20:58.557
You deserve it.

20:58.558 --> 20:59.958
Yeah, and what about Bishop?

20:59.959 --> 21:01.359
He's a hack.

21:01.360 --> 21:03.996
Guy writes six mediocre books.

21:05.331 --> 21:06.932
All of a sudden,
he comes up with one

21:06.933 --> 21:09.501
that people actually buy.
It's bullshit.

21:09.502 --> 21:12.003
(SIGHS) You need to get
your head straight.

21:12.004 --> 21:13.438
Take a vacation.

21:13.439 --> 21:15.507
Finish your second novel.

21:15.508 --> 21:17.008
Get inspired.

21:17.009 --> 21:18.577
SIDNEY: It's hard,
I'm telling you, Harold.

21:18.578 --> 21:21.046
It's hard to get inspired.

21:21.047 --> 21:23.849
You want inspiration?
I'll give you inspiration.

21:23.850 --> 21:25.584
- Ladies and gentlemen…
- No, don't…

21:25.585 --> 21:27.085
Your attention, please.

21:27.086 --> 21:31.556
Mr. Sidney Hall is a finalist
for the Pulitzer Prize.

21:31.557 --> 21:34.459
Give it up
for Mr. Sidney Hall.

21:34.460 --> 21:36.095
(PEOPLE CHEERING)

21:37.196 --> 21:38.497
You had to do that, huh?

21:38.498 --> 21:41.333
- You just had to do…
- That wasn't so bad, was it?

21:41.334 --> 21:42.968
Listen, Sidney.

21:42.969 --> 21:45.337
Whether you believe it or not,
I'm on your side.

21:45.338 --> 21:47.706
I understand what
you're going through.

21:47.707 --> 21:50.542
I've had three of the ugliest
divorces in American history

21:50.543 --> 21:52.010
and I survived them all.

21:52.011 --> 21:53.378
They're like enemas.

21:53.379 --> 21:54.946
They're uncomfortable
and invasive,

21:54.947 --> 21:57.149
but the next day
you feel like a new man.

21:57.150 --> 21:59.651
You need to find
yourself a muse.

21:59.652 --> 22:02.487
Loosen up, you know what I mean?

22:02.488 --> 22:03.889
I'll round back to you in a bit.

22:03.890 --> 22:06.659
Don't leave. I want you
to meet my daughter.

22:09.128 --> 22:10.530
(SIGHS)

22:14.033 --> 22:15.500
Hey, hey. Excuse me.

22:15.501 --> 22:16.902
Yeah, um…

22:16.903 --> 22:18.503
Could you…
Could you send this drink,

22:18.504 --> 22:20.739
while you're there,
could you send it

22:20.740 --> 22:23.808
over to that girl right there?

22:23.809 --> 22:25.210
Black hair.

22:25.211 --> 22:26.279
Thank you.

22:34.187 --> 22:35.253
WAITRESS: This is for you

22:35.254 --> 22:37.355
from the gentleman
in the corner.

22:37.356 --> 22:38.991
Right there.

22:59.779 --> 23:02.013
You couldn't just walk 15 feet
and give it to me yourself?

23:02.014 --> 23:05.717
You had to send it over
from a safe distance?

23:05.718 --> 23:08.086
Is that part of the…

23:08.087 --> 23:11.324
Sidney Hall mystique?

23:13.960 --> 23:15.927
What's your name?

23:15.928 --> 23:16.928
Alexandra.

23:17.563 --> 23:19.397
If you don't wanna
take the drink,

23:19.398 --> 23:22.334
I'll gladly take it from…

23:22.335 --> 23:23.603
You.

24:22.795 --> 24:24.063
- (WHISTLE BLOWS)
- (GRUNTING)

24:31.804 --> 24:33.172
Okay.

24:34.507 --> 24:36.207
You have to leave
Lewis Chang alone.

24:36.208 --> 24:37.709
I don't even want
to see you looking at him.

24:37.710 --> 24:41.313
That goes for Greg and Pyat
and all the other goons.

24:41.314 --> 24:43.014
(LAUGHS)

24:43.015 --> 24:44.182
What do you care about him for?

24:44.183 --> 24:46.484
I mean, look at him,
he's asking for it.

24:46.485 --> 24:49.155
I don't see him asking for it.

24:51.357 --> 24:53.793
Fine. Whatever, Hall… Look.

24:54.593 --> 24:55.960
You better shed
some serious light

24:55.961 --> 24:57.529
on the situation
if I'm going to throw away

24:57.530 --> 25:00.298
one of the few things I have
to look forward to every day.

25:00.299 --> 25:02.435
Does that mean you'll stop?

25:04.437 --> 25:05.705
Yeah, I'll stop.

25:07.340 --> 25:08.540
But if he ever grows
enough balls

25:08.541 --> 25:09.607
to start up with me,
I swear to God…

25:09.608 --> 25:10.842
Yeah. Yeah. Yeah…

25:10.843 --> 25:12.544
You'll shove his dick
up his ass or whatever.

25:12.545 --> 25:14.113
He's not gonna start with you.

25:16.282 --> 25:17.849
We have a deal?

25:17.850 --> 25:19.251
I'll pick you up Saturday.

25:21.287 --> 25:23.289
You live over in Cedar, right?

25:24.290 --> 25:25.891
Yeah.

25:26.359 --> 25:27.426
Across the tracks,

25:28.861 --> 25:31.097
as my dad would say.

25:32.565 --> 25:34.166
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

25:43.909 --> 25:45.543
Dad?

25:45.544 --> 25:47.179
Yeah.

25:51.550 --> 25:53.151
Never mind.

25:53.152 --> 25:54.487
(CAR HONKS)

26:26.819 --> 26:29.221
(HOUSE DOOR CLOSES)

26:37.797 --> 26:39.298
No! No, no, wait!

26:45.438 --> 26:46.539
(DOOR CLOSES)

27:00.786 --> 27:02.720
(WHISPERS) Jameson.

27:02.721 --> 27:04.089
Jameson.

27:10.796 --> 27:13.165
(DIAL TONE RINGING)

27:18.704 --> 27:20.104
Hello.

27:20.105 --> 27:22.541
Hi. Hi, is this, uh, Melody?

27:31.484 --> 27:33.084
(HANGS UP)

27:33.085 --> 27:34.286
Shit.

27:58.744 --> 28:00.546
SIDNEY: This guy is good.

28:02.481 --> 28:04.984
This guy's really fucking good.

28:05.718 --> 28:07.285
You, sir,

28:07.286 --> 28:09.455
have been drinking
since I met you.

28:10.956 --> 28:12.457
It's a very bad habit.

28:12.458 --> 28:13.791
And incidentally, I'm getting

28:13.792 --> 28:16.561
kinda tired of pretending like
we don't know each other

28:16.562 --> 28:18.463
every time we go out in public.

28:18.464 --> 28:20.064
I'm sorta married.

28:20.065 --> 28:22.333
Are you sorta divorced?

28:22.334 --> 28:23.569
Sorta separated?

28:26.472 --> 28:27.739
You're Harold's daughter.

28:27.740 --> 28:29.507
I think he can handle it.

28:29.508 --> 28:31.576
You're his meal ticket, so…

28:31.577 --> 28:33.112
Maybe today.

28:33.612 --> 28:35.013
Okay.

28:35.014 --> 28:38.683
I think you should take one
of these and some of this.

28:38.684 --> 28:41.753
Gonna get some sleep, and then
tomorrow's going to happen…

28:41.754 --> 28:43.821
I'm tired of sleeping.

28:43.822 --> 28:45.523
My entire life,
I can't think of one

28:45.524 --> 28:50.129
positive dreaming experience,
only nightmares.

28:51.230 --> 28:52.764
Is there any
particular nightmare

28:52.765 --> 28:54.633
that I can help you with?

28:57.036 --> 29:01.873
Well there's this one,
recurring one.

29:01.874 --> 29:03.608
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

29:03.609 --> 29:05.477
Where I'm being followed.

29:10.783 --> 29:14.485
SIDNEY: Everywhere I go.
He's with me.

29:14.486 --> 29:18.157
And I get claustrophobic.

29:19.325 --> 29:21.694
Like he's

29:22.628 --> 29:24.062
strangling me.

29:24.063 --> 29:28.600
Like he knows all the bad
things that I've ever done.

29:28.601 --> 29:30.569
And he's coming to judge me.

29:31.437 --> 29:33.271
And when I wake up
from this nightmare,

29:33.272 --> 29:35.274
he's still there.

29:38.243 --> 29:40.212
I don't know what he wants.

29:40.980 --> 29:44.183
But he knows
everything about me.

29:46.685 --> 29:48.886
That's what scares me the most.

29:48.887 --> 29:50.623
Good morning.

29:53.826 --> 29:54.959
SEARCHER: Mr. Tidemand.

29:54.960 --> 29:58.397
I wonder if you
by chance know…

29:59.465 --> 30:01.400
This man.

30:05.838 --> 30:09.074
Have you seen him recently,
Mr. Tidemand?

30:11.410 --> 30:14.045
I'd like you to take a good
long look at this mug shot

30:14.046 --> 30:16.714
because it was taken
very recently.

30:16.715 --> 30:18.850
Okay, so?

30:18.851 --> 30:22.053
No one has claimed to see
or hear from Sidney Hall

30:22.054 --> 30:24.188
in over five years.

30:24.189 --> 30:27.125
And yet here he is, posing.

30:27.126 --> 30:28.793
For New York City
Police Department.

30:28.794 --> 30:30.329
Now how is that possible?

30:31.997 --> 30:33.732
He was booked
under another name.

30:39.271 --> 30:40.805
JOHAN:
What do you want from me?

30:40.806 --> 30:42.707
What I want to know,
Mr. Tidemand,

30:42.708 --> 30:45.943
is if there are things
that you make,

30:45.944 --> 30:49.348
other than these beautiful

30:51.583 --> 30:53.085
wood trolls.

30:55.487 --> 30:57.089
It's a trick.

30:58.924 --> 30:59.992
What is?

31:00.325 --> 31:02.994
I think you know
what I'm talking about.

31:02.995 --> 31:04.862
I'm not after you,
Mr. Tidemand.

31:04.863 --> 31:06.431
I'd like to offer you a trade.

31:06.432 --> 31:09.500
You give me the information
about the documents you forged

31:09.501 --> 31:10.868
for Sidney Hall.

31:10.869 --> 31:12.303
And I give you my word,

31:12.304 --> 31:15.340
you will never see me again.

31:16.141 --> 31:19.644
All right,
but just so we're clear,

31:19.645 --> 31:21.446
this conversation
is being recorded

31:21.447 --> 31:23.115
on both sides of the table.

31:24.283 --> 31:25.484
Fair enough.

31:38.263 --> 31:39.198
(TAPE REWINDS, CLICKS)

31:39.199 --> 31:41.065
JOHAN: …was here
a few months ago.

31:41.066 --> 31:41.934
SEARCHER: And?

31:41.935 --> 31:43.568
JOHAN:
I made him a couple ID's,

31:43.569 --> 31:46.537
a passport
and a drivers license.

31:46.538 --> 31:47.905
SEARCHER: What else?

31:47.906 --> 31:49.741
JOHAN: He didn't look good.

31:49.742 --> 31:52.910
He said he had some
loose ends to tie up.

31:52.911 --> 31:54.512
SEARCHER: Did he say
where he was going?

31:54.513 --> 31:55.913
JOHAN: No, that's all I know.

31:55.914 --> 31:57.416
(CAR ENGINE STARTS)

32:32.785 --> 32:34.086
SIDNEY: Hey! Hey!

32:36.488 --> 32:37.956
No crossing the street.

32:38.957 --> 32:40.058
Okay.

32:40.425 --> 32:41.527
Okay.

32:43.529 --> 32:44.963
I just…

32:47.232 --> 32:48.467
Is your name Melody?

32:52.638 --> 32:53.972
Have we met before?

32:57.142 --> 32:58.243
Yes.

32:59.278 --> 33:00.345
We met.

33:01.480 --> 33:02.815
When?

33:04.917 --> 33:06.051
In the first grade.

33:06.852 --> 33:10.621
You gave me a Valentines Day
card on the wrong day.

33:10.622 --> 33:11.923
And then

33:11.924 --> 33:15.760
on the actual Valentines Day,
you kissed me.

33:15.761 --> 33:17.196
And I told on you.

33:18.297 --> 33:20.832
And I would have kissed
you back, the next day…

33:20.833 --> 33:24.469
But we moved. We went south
for a little bit.

33:26.438 --> 33:27.606
Now you've moved back?

33:32.077 --> 33:34.046
Why do you keep
running away from me?

33:37.616 --> 33:39.117
I don't know.

33:41.353 --> 33:42.921
Because it's fun.

33:44.423 --> 33:45.423
Maybe I'm afraid.

33:46.458 --> 33:48.993
- Afraid of what?
- Uh! No crossing the street.

33:48.994 --> 33:50.728
All right. All right, I won't.

33:50.729 --> 33:52.064
I just…

33:53.565 --> 33:57.069
When can I cross the street?

34:01.773 --> 34:03.141
(CAMERA CLICKS)

34:14.052 --> 34:15.286
(GRUNTS)

34:15.286 --> 34:17.456
(CAR APPROACHING)

34:18.790 --> 34:21.025
- (CAR DOOR OPENS AND SHUTS)
- (SIGHS)

34:29.868 --> 34:31.601
What the fuck you doing, Hall?

34:31.603 --> 34:34.038
I was having a moment.

34:34.039 --> 34:35.505
Until you showed up.

34:35.507 --> 34:36.608
Well, come on, let's go.

34:37.576 --> 34:40.078
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING
OVER RADIO)

34:41.513 --> 34:43.080
You wanna smoke?

34:43.081 --> 34:44.216
No.

34:49.688 --> 34:51.322
What's that, a journal?

34:52.056 --> 34:52.991
Yup.

34:52.992 --> 34:54.926
How long you kept one of those?

34:54.927 --> 34:56.995
Since I was five.

35:00.032 --> 35:02.366
You know, I wasn't
lying to you before.

35:02.367 --> 35:03.702
About the essay.

35:04.503 --> 35:06.170
I loved that shit, man.

35:06.171 --> 35:07.972
All that stuff you rant about

35:07.973 --> 35:10.975
in the school paper,
shit makes me laugh.

35:10.976 --> 35:13.044
You should write about me.

35:13.045 --> 35:15.614
Oh, yeah? What would
that be about?

35:16.748 --> 35:17.748
My father.

35:18.483 --> 35:20.718
Your father? What about him?

35:20.719 --> 35:22.487
You know who my father is?

35:23.822 --> 35:25.324
Yeah, he's a… He's a judge.

35:26.658 --> 35:29.427
So what, doesn't mean I should
write a book about him.

35:29.428 --> 35:31.730
Doesn't make you any
more interesting either.

35:37.736 --> 35:39.071
Whatever, man.

35:41.073 --> 35:44.442
You'll be singing
a different tune tomorrow.

35:44.443 --> 35:45.644
(INCREASES MUSIC VOLUME)

35:46.878 --> 35:48.480
What happens tomorrow?

36:02.794 --> 36:04.396
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

36:11.503 --> 36:12.738
May I come in?

36:13.672 --> 36:14.406
Yeah.

36:14.407 --> 36:16.307
DUANE:
Your elevator's stuck again.

36:16.308 --> 36:17.908
- (DOOR SHUTS)
- Oh, Duane,

36:17.909 --> 36:20.012
it's 6:00 in the morning.

36:20.612 --> 36:22.580
(GRUNTS) Not in Oklahoma.

36:22.581 --> 36:23.914
Great.

36:23.915 --> 36:26.150
"The night served
as a tragic setting

36:26.151 --> 36:27.586
"in the town of Oklahoma City

36:28.653 --> 36:31.188
"where an aspiring writer,
Henry Crowe,

36:31.189 --> 36:33.225
"committed suicide
in front of his parents.

36:34.259 --> 36:36.627
"After a failed attempt
to kill his step-father

36:36.628 --> 36:37.729
"with a 9mm handgun,

36:39.164 --> 36:40.865
"he turned the gun on himself

36:40.866 --> 36:43.134
- and shot himself in the head."
- I don't understand.

36:43.135 --> 36:45.302
"The only thing found
on his person

36:45.303 --> 36:48.072
"was a paperback copy
of Suburban Tragedy

36:48.073 --> 36:50.308
"by renowned author,
Sidney Hall.

36:54.312 --> 36:56.547
"He owned no less than
eight copies of the novel

36:56.548 --> 36:57.915
"and according to friends,

36:57.916 --> 37:00.118
"often quoted passages
from the book.

37:01.186 --> 37:04.155
"Henry Crowe is one of
many in a growing allegiance

37:04.156 --> 37:06.357
"of Suburban Tragedy followers

37:06.358 --> 37:07.591
"who take the book so literally

37:07.592 --> 37:10.327
"that they will attempt
to mimic its message

37:10.328 --> 37:12.997
"and expose the underbelly
of Suburban America

37:12.998 --> 37:14.799
"no matter what the cost.

37:14.800 --> 37:20.304
"The book has already been
banned in school libraries

37:20.305 --> 37:22.441
"and teaching curriculums
in Montana.

37:23.508 --> 37:25.342
"And this incident
will undoubtedly

37:25.343 --> 37:27.712
"spiral its resistance upwards,

37:29.748 --> 37:31.817
"Possibly at
a national level."

37:37.189 --> 37:38.790
How young was he?

37:40.559 --> 37:43.261
- It doesn't make a difference.
- How young was he?

37:45.697 --> 37:47.332
Twenty-two.

37:47.933 --> 37:49.568
(SIGHS)

37:52.104 --> 37:53.971
This book
has inspired more people

37:53.972 --> 37:55.272
than you can possibly…

37:55.273 --> 37:57.708
Inspired people to do what?
Kill themselves?

37:57.709 --> 38:01.278
Whatever happens over
the next few weeks,

38:01.279 --> 38:02.580
this is not your fault.

38:02.581 --> 38:04.315
They'll make it my fault.

38:04.316 --> 38:06.417
Maybe.
For a news cycle, but…

38:06.418 --> 38:08.252
You don't read
the Internet anyway, okay,

38:08.253 --> 38:10.722
so just… Just continue that.

38:11.756 --> 38:13.792
Continue that, all right?

38:33.979 --> 38:35.546
DALE: Now, this book

38:35.547 --> 38:38.449
is essentially feeding our youth

38:38.450 --> 38:40.484
- a dangerously blind idealism.
- (TYPEWRITER CLACKING)

38:40.485 --> 38:42.052
Promoting disrespect
for our elders.

38:42.053 --> 38:44.321
A generation
bred on entitlement.

38:44.322 --> 38:45.623
And the fact
that it's being included

38:45.624 --> 38:47.124
in our school curriculum

38:47.125 --> 38:49.693
is a dangerous sign
of the times.

38:49.694 --> 38:52.429
